Interface VFunctionsAndVUnboundMethods


  • public interface VFunctionsAndVUnboundMethods
    An interface with no abstract or default methods that bundles "voidable" VFunction and VUnboundMethod interfaces and static methods that convert fully typed to "voidable" functional and unbound method types.

    A "voidable" type is a generic type which can have the equivalent of a void type as a possible type value. There are two kinds of voidable type, each with its own distinctive class as singleton instance:

    • Type VoidA, instance voidA - type/value that can be passed as argument as the equivalent of no ("void") argument
    • Type VoidR, instance voidR - type/value that can be returned as the equivalent no ("void") return
    Author:
    John Armstrong

      A "voidable" unbound methoid interface which takes, in addtional to an initial class instance argument, two arguments of any generic types <A1,A2> and returns a value of any generic type <R> including VoidR.
      static interface  VFunctionsAndVUnboundMethods.VFunction<A,R>
      A "voidable" functional interface which takes no arg or a single arg which may be of any generic type <A> including VoidA and returns a value of any generic type <R> including VoidR.
      static class  VFunctionsAndVUnboundMethods.VoidA
      Class of void argument (possible in C and C++ function/method declarations though not in Java).
      static class  VFunctionsAndVUnboundMethods.VoidR
      Class of void return value (a standard feature of C, C++ and Java function/method declarations).
      static interface  VFunctionsAndVUnboundMethods.VTriFunction<A1,A2,A3,R>
      A "voidable" functional interface which takes three args any generic types <A1,A2,A3> and returns a value of any generic type <R> including VoidR.
      static interface  VFunctionsAndVUnboundMethods.VUnboundMethod<C,A,R>
      A "voidable" unbound method interface which takes, after an initial class instance arg, no arg or a single arg which may be of any generic type <A> including VoidA and returns a value of any generic type <R> including VoidR.

    • Field Detail

      • voidA

        static final VFunctionsAndVUnboundMethods.VoidA voidA
        Void argument value - the one and only instance of class VoidA. Represents a pseudo-argument that can optionally be passed to a vFunction made from a functional object which takes no arguments - compare function(void) signatures in C and C++.

      • voidR

        static final VFunctionsAndVUnboundMethods.VoidR voidR
        Void return value - the one and only instance of class VoidR. Represents the result of calling a vFunction made from a functional object with void return type.

      • makeVFunction

        static <R> VFunctionsAndVUnboundMethods.VFunction<VFunctionsAndVUnboundMethods.VoidA,R> makeVFunction(Callable<R> callable)
        Converts a Callable functional object to a VFunction. Result can be called with no argument or with a single argument voidA, and will return the value returned by the wrapped callable object. Catches any checked exception thrown by the callable object and rethrows it as a runtime exception. (Callable is the only standard Java functional interfaces which throws a checked exception.)

        This and the method @link #makeVFunction(Supplier) both accept function objects that take no argument and return values that do not declare a checked exception. A cast can be used to force one override over the other.

        Type Parameters:
        R - the generic return type of the passed supplier object
        Parameters:
        callable - a lambda expression, bound method, or implementation of the standard Callable interface
        Returns:
        a VFunction which wraps the callable object

        Converts a Supplier functional object to a VFunction. Result can be called with no argument or with a single argument voidA, and will return the value returned by the wrapped supplier.

        This and the method @link #makeVFunction(Callable) both accept function objects that take no argument and return a value that do not declare a checked exception. A cast can be used to force one override over the other.
